Phase 1: Preparation and Extraction
Porcini Hydration: Place the dried porcini in a small bowl and cover with  cup of near-boiling water.43 Allow to steep for 30 minutes.43 Once softened, remove the porcini, chop finely, and reserve.40 CRITICAL: Strain the soaking liquid through a coffee filter to remove all sand and silt; this liquid is a "nucleotide concentrate" and must be added to the soup later.40
Mushroom Cleaning: Use a damp paper towel or a quick rinse in a salad spinner to clean the fresh mushrooms.23 Ensure they are thoroughly dried before slicing; any surface moisture will delay the Maillard reaction.20
Slicing: Slice cremini and shiitake to exactly -inch.6 This thickness provides enough surface area for browning while maintaining enough internal moisture to prevent shriveling before the Maillard reaction completes.6

Phase 2: The Searing Protocol (Thermal Management)
Pan Preheating: Place a heavy  or -quart Dutch oven over medium-high heat.22 Using an infrared thermometer, wait until the center of the pan reaches  to .22
Batch Searing: Add  of ghee/avocado oil. Add enough mushrooms to cover the bottom in a single layer (approx.  of the mushrooms).25 Do not stir immediately.25 Let them sear for 3-4 minutes until they release their water and the pan begins to sizzle again.25
Maillard Development: Once the pan sounds "sharp" (sizzling vs. bubbling), the water has evaporated.26 Stir and cook for another 5 minutes until the mushrooms are a deep mahogany brown.25 Transfer to a bowl and repeat in two more batches with remaining ghee and mushrooms.25

Phase 3: The Aromatic Build
Sweating Alliums: Reduce the heat to medium ( to  pan temp).59 Add  of the grass-fed butter. Add the leeks and shallots.4 Sauté for 6-8 minutes until soft and translucent.4 Do not brown them deeply; the goal here is sweetness and softening of the sulfur compounds.4
Garlic and Herbs: Add the minced garlic, minced sage, and  of kosher salt.15 Cook for only 60 seconds until the garlic is fragrant but not brown.15

Phase 4: Deglazing and Infusion
Deglazing: Increase heat to high and pour in the  cup of dry white vermouth or sherry.44 Use a wooden scraper to lift the "fond" (the brown bits) from the bottom of the pan—this is concentrated Maillard byproduct.47 Reduce the liquid by  until it is a thick syrup.44
Liquid Incorporation: Return all seared mushrooms (and any accumulated juices) to the pot. Add the chopped porcini, the strained porcini soaking liquid, and the 5 cups of chicken bone broth.4
Simmering: Add the Parmesan rind, the thyme bundle, and the tamari.16 Bring to a boil, then immediately reduce to a very low simmer.19 The liquid should be approximately  to .19 Cover partially and simmer for 45 minutes.41

Phase 5: The Puree and Emulsification (Structural Transformation)
The Extraction: Remove and discard the Parmesan rind and the thyme bundle.44
The High-Shear Blend: For the best results, use a high-powered countertop blender in batches.1 Fill the blender only halfway and use a kitchen towel to hold down the lid (to prevent steam pressure explosions).1
Fiber Breakdown: Blend on the highest speed for a full 90 seconds.6 This is the step where the chitin cell walls are shredded into nanofibers, providing the starch-free thickness.6 The soup should change from a chunky broth to a thick, frothy, velvety cream.38
Emulsification: While the blender is running on a lower speed, add the remaining  of cold grass-fed butter.67 This "mounts" the soup with fat, creating a glossy, stable emulsion.67

Phase 6: Finishing and Seasoning
Cream Addition: Return the pureed soup to the pot over low heat. Whisk in the heavy cream.6
The "Correction": Stir in the miso paste (whisked with a little hot soup first to avoid lumps) and the fresh nutmeg.4
Acid and Salt: Taste the soup. Add salt and pepper until the flavors "pop." Add the  of lemon juice.44 Acidity is the "secret weapon" that balances the heavy lipids and fungal earthiness.44

The Physics of Emulsion and Reheating Stability
One of the primary challenges for the home chef is maintaining the "luscious" texture during service or upon reheating. Because this soup relies on a protein-and-fiber emulsion rather than a starch gel, it is more sensitive to temperature fluctuations.4
Temperature Thresholds for Stable Lipids
The butter-in-water emulsion of the soup is most stable when held between  and .62 If the soup is brought to a hard boil () after the cream and butter are added, the proteins in the dairy may coagulate and the fat droplets may coalesce, causing the soup to "break" or become oily.2
To reheat: Use a low flame and stir constantly until the soup reaches —the safe serving temperature that also preserves the emulsion's integrity.32
Using Hydrocolloids as a Safety Net
While the mushroom fiber (chitin) provides significant thickness, the viscosity may vary depending on the specific mushroom variety used. If the soup appears too thin after blending, the use of xanthan gum at a concentration of  (approx.  for a -quart batch) can provide a "safety net".29 Xanthan gum is a cold-soluble polysaccharide that does not require heat to activate and provides excellent stability for fat-heavy emulsions.54
Mycological Variety Comparison and Sourcing
For the home chef, the "best" recipe is often limited by grocery store availability. However, understanding the characteristics of different mushrooms allows for intelligent substitutions.

